sp;&nbsp;<span>The elephant in the <s>room</s> thread</span></div><article class="post h-entry"><div class="containbox" style="margin:auto; position:relative; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom:20px; width:98%; background-color:var(--background-color);"><div style="float:left;"><a href="/about" class="p-author"><img class="ppic" src="https://shellsharks-images.s3.amazonaws.com/surfshark.png" width="60" alt="author-image" ></a></div><div style="float:left;"><span id="author" style="font-weight:bold;">Mike Sass</span><br><span id="handle" style="color:var(--light-font-color);">@shellsharks</span></div><div style="float:right;padding:10px 0px 0px 0px;"><i class="ph ph-calendar-dot"></i> <span id="date" style="font-size:0.75em;" class="dt-published">3/27/24 15:03</span></div><br><br><br><header id="header" class="post-header"></header><div class="post-content e-content"><p>A common myth about elephants is that they are afraid of mice. But would a <a href="https://joinmastodon.org">Mastodon</a> (<em>a prehistoric elephant</em>) be afraid of a <a href="https://join-lemmy.org">Lemmy</a> (<em>the mascot being a mouse-like rodent</em>)? In the <a href="https://www.fediverse.to">Fediverse</a>, the answer to this is a definitive “<em>No</em>”! One (of many) thing(s) that is so interesting and powerful about the Fediverse and the platforms that comprise it is the way in which they can interact with one another, thanks to their common ability to speak <a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/activitypub/">ActivityPub</a>. One such example is using Mastodon to interact with Lemmy threads.<p>There are a number of reasons you might want to respond to a Lemmy thread/comment with your Mastodon handle…<ul><li>You don’t want to create a Lemmy account<li>You want to use your primary Fediverse identity rather than having a separate Lemmy-based account<li>It’s easier for you to respond and maintain a discussion directly within your Mastodon client<li>…<em>and more</em>!</ul><p>Since setting off on my own via my <a href="https://shellsharks.social">single-account Mastodon instance</a>, I’ve been more interested in <a href="/own-my-social">centralizing</a> my interactions on the Fediverse to a single <a href="https://shellsharks.social/@shellsharks">account</a>. As such, I wanted to experiment a <a href="/threadiversal-travel#interactivity-w-mastodon">little bit more</a> with how I could interact with the various Lemmy <a href="/threadiversal-travel#communities">communities</a> that I am active in. So here’s some quick observations I’ve made after playing with a few things in the Mastodon-to-Lemmy world…<ul><li>Some <a href="/threadiversal-travel#interactivity-w-mastodon">earlier observations</a> about interactivity between Mastodon and Lemmy hold true.<li>You can follow an entire Lemmy community, i.e. <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">@COMMUNITY@SERVER</code>.<li>You can <em>browse</em> communities from within Mastodon by searching for <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">@COMMUNITY@SERVER</code>. What you will see is a list of thread posts and thread comments all <em>boosted</em> by the community handle. It’s not the most intuitive interface, but it <em>does</em> work.<li>You can reply to any of the parent thread posts, or child comments directly in Mastodon as if they were just Mastodon posts. These appear inline within Lemmy as if they were a comment from any other native Lemmy account.<li>You can reply to threads/comments that are on instances that you don’t have an account on, even those that are behind invite-only registration walls!<li>Comments on Lemmy posts are shown as boosts from the Lemmy community handle in my Mastodon timeline</ul><p>Some pitfalls, challenges and things to consider if you are going to try and interact with Lemmy using Mastodon…<ul><li>Federation is hard to wrap your head around and it gets even more complex when you think about how things make their way between different Lemmy servers, Mastodon instance, etc… As such, you may have no problem finding content on one Lemmy server on a particular Mastodon instance but have trouble in other situations. In my case, I was unable to find things on my small personal instance but <em>was</em> able to find it on larger instances.<ul><li>To mitigate this so I could respond from my personal account, I would “simply” (admittedly kind of a janky hack) switch over to the Mastodon account on the larger server, find the Lemmy post I wanted to reply to from my smaller Mastodon instance and then reply to that thread as DM to my smaller Mastodon account. Doing that would kick off some kind of federation event so my small account could see that Lemmy thread. Weird! But hey it works.</ul><li>I also observed another in-Lemmy federation quirk. I submitted a post on infosec.pub by my infosec.pub account. A Lemmy user from <em>another</em> server left a comment on that post. I then responded to <em>that</em> comment using my Mastodon account. That Mastodon-based reply propagated to the <em>other</em> Lemmy user’s server but did not show up on the infosec.pub server. Weird!</ul><p>If you’re confused, don’t worry, I’m still confused too. Happy cross-platform postin’ y’all!</div><div style="bottom:-5px; text-align:right;font-size:0.75em;"><i class="ph ph-pencil"></i> 630</div><hr style="opacity:35%;margin-top: 10px;margin-bottom: 10px;width:75%;"><div id="info" class="wrapper"><div class="box 1" style="background-color:var(--background-color);"><div><i class="ph ph-map-pin-area" title="Posted from"></i> <span id="posted-from" style="font-size:0.75em;">Ivory for Mac</span></div><div><i class="ph ph-broadcast"></i><span style="font-size:0.75em;"> Syndication:</span></div><div style="font-size:1.5em;"><span id="syndicate-to"> <span style="padding:0px 3px 0px 3px;"><a href="https://shellsharks.social/@shellsharks/112169245923684337"><i class="ph ph-mastodon-logo" title="Mastodon"></i></a></span> </span></div></div><div class="box2" style="bottom:0;"><div style="text-align:right; padding:5px 5px 5px 5px;"><a class="u-url" href=""><i class="ph ph-link" title="Permalink"></i></a> <a href="/notebook"><i class="ph ph-book-open" title="Notebook"></i></a> <a href="/"><i class="ph ph-house" title="Home"></i></a></div><div style="font-size:0.75em;color:var(--light-font-color);padding:5px 5px 0px 5px;text-align:right;"><i class="ph ph-tag"></i> <span id="tags" style="padding:0px 3px 0px 3px;"><a href="/tags?tag=fediverse">#fediverse</a></span> <span id="tags" style="padding:0px 3px 0px 3px;"><a href="/tags?tag=lemmy">#lemmy</a></span> <span id="tags" style="padding:0px 3px 0px 3px;"><a href="/tags?tag=threadiverse">#threadiverse</a></span> <span id="tags" style="padding:0px 3px 0px 3px;"><a href="/tags?tag=mastodon">#mastodon</a></span></div></div></div></div></article><div style="margin-bottom:20px; margin-right:5px; margin-left:5px;"> <a class="prev" style="margin-right: 2em; margin-left:8px;" href="/notes/2024/03/26/shellsharks-toot-archive#title">&laquo; shellsharks@infosec.exchange toot archive</a><div style="float:right;"><a class="next" href="/notes/2024/03/28/shellsharks-social-112173560083302070#title" style="margin-right: 8px;">shellsharks.social 3/28/24 09:31 EDT &raquo;</a></div></div><style> .wrapper { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; } img {max-width:100%}</style></div></main><aside class="container_item"></aside><footer class="container_item"> <center><span style="color:var(--light-font-color); font-size:.8em; font-style:italic; position:relative; top:25px;">Brought to you with <i class="ph-fill ph-heart-straight" style="color:var(--accent-color);"></i> by <a href="https://shellsharks.com/about">Shellsharks</a></span></center> <center> <img id="sharkfooter" src="/assets/img/sharks-circling.png" alt="Circling Sharks" style="width:150px;"></img> </center></footer></div><noscript><div class="panel" align="center" style="font-weight:bold;"><h1>Please enable JavaScript.</h1></div></noscript> <